Difference between Build Now and Build with Parameters?

Build Now — runs immediately with default/hardcoded values, no user input, no form shown.

Build with Parameters — shows a form before running where you fill ENV, IMAGE_TAG etc., 
pipeline uses ${params.ENV} to decide which cluster, which ECR, which namespace to deploy to.

One repo, one Jenkinsfile, one deployment.yaml — two environments

GitHub repo (single source of truth)
    ├── Jenkinsfile        ← same pipeline for both
    ├── Dockerfile         ← same image build for both
    ├── deployment.yaml    ← same manifest, placeholders replaced at runtime
    └── src/               ← same code for both

What changes at runtime — not in Git

Build with Parameters
        │
        ├── ENV = uat
        │       │
        │       ├── aws-creds-uat        → 111111111111 ECR
        │       ├── IMAGE_PLACEHOLDER    → 111111111111.dkr.ecr.../myapp:v1.0.0
        │       ├── ENV_PLACEHOLDER      → uat
        │       └── kubectl              → uat-cluster, namespace uat
        │
        └── ENV = prod
                │
                ├── aws-creds-prod       → 222222222222 ECR
                ├── IMAGE_PLACEHOLDER    → 222222222222.dkr.ecr.../myapp:v1.0.0
                ├── ENV_PLACEHOLDER      → prod
                └── kubectl              → prod-cluster, namespace prod

Typical release flow using this setup

Dev pushes code to GitHub
        │
        ▼
Jenkins → Build with Parameters → ENV=uat → Build
        │
        ▼
UAT team tests
        │
        ▼
UAT sign off ✅
        │
        ▼
Jenkins → Build with Parameters → ENV=prod → same IMAGE_TAG → Build
        │
        ▼
Prod Approval gate → manager clicks Approve
        │
        ▼
Same image promoted to PROD cluster
